    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Curacao</placeName>
                <date>5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> March 1853</date>
            </p>
            <p>To the <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">As <persName>Mr. Elias Lindo</persName>, has<lb/> just received a
                letter for Ocean Bird, from <persName>Mr Seixas</persName> of <placeName>N
                    Y</placeName>,<lb/> acknowledging the receipt of the Box of Books and as
                    <persName>Mr E.<lb/> Lindo</persName> himself has written to you, long since,
                explaining the<lb/> cause of its detention, there appears no necessity for my
                saying<lb/> any thing further on the subject, than to regret the annoyance<lb/> it
                has occasioned you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In a very short time I hope to have the pleasure<lb/> of sending you
                for insertion in the Occident, an account of<lb/> the formation of a Hebrew
                benevolent society in this <placeName>Island</placeName><lb/> The matter is yet in
                embargo, only one preliminary meeting having<lb/> as yet been held. As to the
                account of the founding of the<lb/> Synagogue, I regret to add, that it is beyond my
                power to furnish<lb/> it, <persName>Mr Miranda</persName> the Secretary
                <add>?</add>, that the editor<lb/> of the “Archives Israelites” applied to him for
                similar information<lb/> which he was unable to send, in consequence of the Records
                and<lb/> Books being completely destroyed <del>dest</del> by Ants, and the
                dampness<lb/> of the climate. I am indebted to you for 1 doz Catechisms, “Road to
                faith”<lb/> but the price for which I have forgotten, send it on if you please,
                and<lb/> I will send it together with the Amot, of the subscription for the<lb/>
                Occident, from myself and others. I have only succeeded in</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>in obtaining one more subscriber <persName>Mr E Edwards</persName>, but at the
                same<lb/> time have prevented another from giving it up. Allow me to<lb/> observe
                that, wordy warfare such as is contained in your last No.<lb/> is any thing but
                agreeable or interesting to your Readers in this<lb/> little
                    <placeName>Island</placeName>, and I also think, you lower your own dignity<lb/>
                by waging it with such an antagonist as <persName>Mr S Jacobs</persName><lb/> This
                is <hi rend="underline">entre nous</hi>, if he is the same man who was lately in
                    <placeName>Kingston<lb/> Jamaica</placeName>, Make a diligent
                <sic>enquiry</sic>, and you will find I have<lb/> just grounds for my advice. I must
                confess, I am taking<lb/> a great liberty with you, but I feel an interest in the
                success<lb/> of your undertakings, Every prudent man ought to examine<lb/> well,
                whether he is going to attack a Bee Hive or a Hornet's Nest<lb/> with kind regard
                and hoping you are well</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">I am</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(10)">
                <persName role="author"><add>?</add> Nathan</persName>
            </p>
            <p>PS. Excuse any illegible writing I can only find time<lb/> to write in the evening
                and my sight fails me at candle<lb/> light</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
        </body>
